# Haven UI/UX + Frontend Execution Rules (v2)

## 0) Authority & document order (non-negotiable)

Read and apply documents in this order:

1. `CLAUDE.md`
   - process law
   - batching
   - tests
   - rollback
   - observability
   - security
2. `docs/design/ART-DIRECTION.md`
   - core art direction
   - token law
   - premium-feel constraints
3. `docs/design/ART-DIRECTION-APPENDIX.md`
   - composition rules
   - component recipes
   - golden screen laws
   - review heuristics
4. this file
   - frontend execution law
   - architecture rules
   - UI quality gate
   - anti-drift rules

### Conflict rule
- process / security / release conflicts → `CLAUDE.md` wins
- aesthetic / token / premium-feel conflicts → `ART-DIRECTION.md` wins
- screen-specific / composition interpretation → `ART-DIRECTION-APPENDIX.md` clarifies
- frontend implementation / component layering / App Router execution → this file wins

Do not ignore earlier documents.
Do not improvise a new design system.

---

## 1) Mandatory read behavior before any UI work

Before writing or editing any UI code, you MUST:

1. read `CLAUDE.md`
2. read `docs/design/ART-DIRECTION.md`
3. if touching layout, forms, dialogs, dashboard, decks, journal, settings, or shared UI patterns:
   - also read `docs/design/ART-DIRECTION-APPENDIX.md`

You must explicitly acknowledge these reads in your output inventory.

### Required acknowledgement format
Include:

- `Read: CLAUDE.md`
- `Read: docs/design/ART-DIRECTION.md`
- `Read: docs/design/ART-DIRECTION-APPENDIX.md` (if applicable)

If you did not read them, do not proceed.

---

## 2) Haven aesthetic execution goal

All frontend work must move Haven toward:

- premium editorial minimalism
- warm emotional modernism
- restrained luxury
- soft material depth
- calm, intimate interaction quality
- non-generic, non-boxy product feel

### Always optimize for:
- hierarchy
- spacing rhythm
- emotional tone
- system consistency
- refined restraint
- premium perceived quality
- usability and accessibility

### Never optimize for:
- trendiness alone
- flashy effects
- “more visual stuff”
- generic SaaS polish
- random Dribbble-style redesign
- decoration without system value

---

## 3) Single source of truth for tokens

## 3.1 Token source
Primary source:
- `frontend/src/app/globals.css`

Optional secondary source:
- theme mappings / Tailwind theme references that consume the semantic CSS variables

### Components must NOT define ad-hoc visual tokens.

---

## 3.2 Token usage rules (hard guardrails)

Use semantic utilities only:
- `bg-background`
- `text-foreground`
- `bg-card`
- `border-border`
- `bg-primary`
- `text-muted-foreground`
- etc.

### Forbidden
- `bg-[#...]`
- `text-[#...]`
- `border-[#...]`
- `text-[rgb(...)]`
- `bg-[oklch(...)]`
- `shadow-[...]`
- ad-hoc radius values
- repeated one-off spacing hacks that should be systematized

### Allowed exception
Only the documented exceptions in `ART-DIRECTION.md` are allowed.

---

## 3.3 OKLCH consistency rule
If a token is stored as an OKLCH triplet in CSS variables:

- export it consistently as `oklch(var(--token))`
- when alpha is needed, use `oklch(var(--token) / <alpha-value>)`
- never wrap OKLCH values with `rgb(...)`

Do not mix token color syntaxes carelessly.

---

## 3.4 Required semantic token groups
At minimum, the system must define and consistently use:

### Color
- `--background`
- `--foreground`
- `--card`
- `--popover`
- `--primary`
- `--secondary`
- `--muted`
- `--accent`
- `--border`
- `--destructive`
- `--ring`

### Typography
- font roles
- heading hierarchy
- body hierarchy
- label/caption hierarchy

### Geometry
- base `--radius`
- derived radii if needed

### Elevation
- `shadow-soft`
- `shadow-lift`
- optional `shadow-modal`

### Motion
- Haven duration token
- Haven easing token

### Space
Must align with:
- `--space-page`
- `--space-section`
- `--space-block`
- `--space-stack`
- `--space-inline`

---

## 4) shadcn/ui customization and component layering

## 4.1 Layering law (no exceptions)

- `frontend/src/components/ui/*`
  - shadcn primitives
  - theme-token aligned
  - low-level reusable UI building blocks

- `frontend/src/components/haven/*`
  - Haven-specific wrappers / variants / compositions
  - premium visual treatment
  - repeated product-level patterns

- feature/page-specific compositions
  - live closer to the feature
  - should not pollute primitives

### Pages and features should prefer `components/haven/*` over raw primitives whenever a Haven-specific pattern already exists.

---

## 4.2 No default shadcn look
Generated shadcn components must be customized to avoid:
- harsh borders
- boxy corners
- default ring behavior
- generic input appearance
- unrefined density
- generic SaaS feel

If a component still looks like “default shadcn,” it is not done.

---

## 4.3 Component family consistency
Buttons, cards, inputs, forms, dialogs, sheets, tabs, badges, nav, lists, empty states, loading states, and error states must feel like one family.

Check consistency across:
- radius
- spacing
- border softness
- shadow style
- type scale
- focus treatment
- hover/active behavior
- motion timing

---

## 4.4 State completeness (required)
Every interactive component must support, as applicable:

- default
- hover
- active
- focus-visible
- disabled
- loading
- error
- selected
- empty (for composite views)

Do not ship components with only the happy-path visual state.

---

## 5) Accessibility (A11y) is mandatory

## 5.1 Keyboard-first UX
Every major screen must be usable without a mouse.

Required:
- correct tab order
- clear focus-visible states
- navigable dialogs/sheets/menus/popovers/comboboxes
- no focus traps unless intentionally managed

---

## 5.2 Form accessibility
- every input must have a label
- `placeholder` is not a label
- `sr-only` labels are acceptable when appropriate
- helper and error text must be connected when relevant

---

## 5.3 Icon-only controls
Every icon-only control must have:
- `aria-label` or
- `aria-labelledby`

`title` is not enough.

---

## 5.4 Focus ring rules
- use `:focus-visible`
- never remove outlines without replacement
- focus treatment must feel premium and visible
- use documented exceptions only when on primary/dark backgrounds

Accessibility is part of product quality, not a polish pass.

---

## 6) Next.js App Router architecture rules

## 6.1 Server-first by default
Default to React Server Components.

Use `'use client'` only where required:
- Zustand hooks
- client-only interactivity
- animation logic
- browser-only APIs
- complex event handling

Do not convert large trees to client components casually.

---

## 6.2 Route segment completeness
Each major route segment should include when appropriate:
- `loading.tsx`
- `error.tsx`
- `not-found.tsx`

These should be designed, not treated as afterthoughts.

Loading, empty, and error states are part of Haven quality.

---

## 6.3 Route organization
Prefer predictable structure such as:
- `frontend/src/app/(marketing)/*`
- `frontend/src/app/(app)/*`

Do not create route chaos or inconsistent page shell patterns.

---

## 6.4 Layout integrity
Do not break:
- layout nesting
- rendering boundaries
- SEO-sensitive surfaces
- performance-sensitive surfaces
- server/client separation

UI polish must not damage architectural correctness.

---

## 7) Data and state rules

## 7.1 TanStack Query
Use for:
- server data fetching
- caching
- mutations
- optimistic updates where appropriate
- consistent loading / empty / error handling

## 7.2 Zustand
Use only for ephemeral client UI state, such as:
- modal open state
- local filters
- command palette
- view mode
- client-side drafts when appropriate

Do NOT duplicate server state in Zustand.

---

## 7.3 State UX rule
Every data-driven surface should explicitly handle:
- loading
- empty
- success
- recoverable error

Do not leave the UI in vague or collapsed states.

---

## 8) Motion and micro-interactions

## 8.1 Motion philosophy
Motion should feel:
- subtle
- calm
- tactile
- premium
- supportive of understanding

It should never feel:
- flashy
- playful in a toy-like way
- excessive
- distracting
- compensatory for weak hierarchy

---

## 8.2 Motion constraints
Prefer:
- opacity
- translate within modest range
- gentle scale
- short duration
- Haven easing

Avoid:
- large bounces
- dramatic overshoot
- long chained animations
- excessive parallax
- gimmicky transitions

---

## 8.3 Interaction defaults
- hover = gentle lift / refinement
- active = subtle press
- loading = skeletons/shimmers preferred over generic spinners
- skeletons must match Haven tone
- reduced-motion users must not be ignored

---

## 9) Forms, empty states, error states, and supportive UX

## 9.1 Forms
Forms must feel:
- calm
- trustworthy
- readable
- grouped
- non-boxy
- emotionally safe

Do not ship:
- raw vertical stacks of default inputs
- crowded label/input/helper/error clusters
- aggressive error styling
- visually mixed destructive actions

---

## 9.2 Empty states
Empty states must include:
- clear hierarchy
- muted but readable tone
- inviting CTA when appropriate
- enough spacing to feel intentional

They must not feel:
- forgotten
- abrupt
- harsh
- generic

---

## 9.3 Error states
Error states should:
- preserve calm
- explain enough
- support recovery
- avoid alarmist styling unless truly necessary

Use inline errors for forms and contextual recovery where possible.

---

## 10) Golden screen execution requirements

If touching any of these screens, also read the appendix and follow its laws:

- Home / Dashboard
- Deck List
- Journal / reflection surfaces
- Settings
- Dialogs / Sheets
- shared form systems

### Requirement
When modifying golden screens, output must explain:
- what premium-feel blockers were addressed
- what composition changes were made
- how the new result aligns with art direction
- what generic patterns were removed

---

## 11) UI Quality Review Rubric (mandatory)

Every UI batch must be evaluated against this rubric.

## 11.1 Hierarchy
- Is there a clear primary focus?
- Is CTA hierarchy obvious?
- Is the page easy to scan?

## 11.2 Spacing rhythm
- Does spacing create calm and cadence?
- Are groups distinct without feeling fragmented?
- Is anything cramped or over-boxed?

## 11.3 Typography
- Are headings, labels, body, caption, and helper text clearly differentiated?
- Does typography feel editorial, not generic?
- Is any metadata too tiny or too low-contrast?

## 11.4 Token compliance
- Any arbitrary colors?
- Any arbitrary shadows?
- Any hardcoded radii?
- Any one-off visual hacks that should be promoted to tokens?

## 11.5 Component consistency
- Do affected components still feel like one product family?
- Any regressions toward default shadcn or generic SaaS?

## 11.6 Emotional tone
- Does the UI feel intimate, calm, premium, and emotionally safe?
- Did the change accidentally make it colder, louder, or more mechanical?

## 11.7 Responsive quality
- Does it stay elegant on desktop, tablet, and mobile?
- Does spacing collapse badly on smaller screens?

## 11.8 Accessibility
- Keyboard path verified?
- Focus-visible verified?
- Labels / aria coverage verified?

If the answer is weak in any of these areas, the batch is not done.

---

## 12) Required output for every UI batch

In addition to `CLAUDE.md`, every frontend/UI response must include:

### Inventory
- repo map
- files to inspect
- files to touch
- explicit acknowledgement of which design docs were read

### Top ROI TODOs
Maximum 3.

Each must include:
- purpose
- user-visible outcome
- design/system impact
- engineering scope
- Definition of Done

### UI Definition of Done (must include all)
- ✅ token compliance check
- ✅ no arbitrary colors/shadows/radii introduced
- ✅ typography hierarchy verified
- ✅ spacing rhythm reviewed
- ✅ focus-visible path verified
- ✅ labels / aria verified
- ✅ loading / empty / error states handled
- ✅ responsive behavior checked
- ✅ premium-feel blockers reduced
- ✅ result still matches Haven art direction

### Batch section
- summary
- risk assessment
- exact files changed
- test plan
- rollback plan
- observability notes if relevant
- assumptions
- open questions

---

## 13) Guardrails against style drift

Do not:
- bypass tokens for convenience
- introduce one-off visual hacks
- create new component styles without checking whether a Haven wrapper should exist
- stack decorative effects to fake premium quality
- rely on borders everywhere to create structure
- create pages with equal-weight visual blocks
- solve hierarchy only with bigger cards and more shadows

### Drift rule
If a new UI pattern appears more than once, it must be systematized.

---

## 14) Definition of “done” for UI implementation

A UI change is done only if:

1. it works functionally
2. it passes lint/build/tests relevant to the batch
3. it preserves App Router and state boundaries
4. it respects tokens and system rules
5. it improves or preserves accessibility
6. it meaningfully improves perceived quality
7. it does not regress into generic SaaS or default shadcn styling

Functional correctness alone is not enough.
Visual prettiness alone is not enough.
“Haven quality” requires both.

---

## 15) Documented exceptions

See `ART-DIRECTION.md` for:
- `global-error.tsx`
- focus ring on primary / dark background exceptions

Do not invent new exceptions here.

---

## 16) Final execution reminder

You are not here to make Haven merely “clean.”
You are here to make it feel:
- crafted
- calm
- premium
- intimate
- elegant
- systemically coherent

Prefer:
- restraint over decoration
- rhythm over stacking
- hierarchy over noise
- system over ad-hoc styling
- emotional safety over harsh efficiency

If something is technically valid but visually generic, it is still wrong.
If something is visually impressive but systemically messy, it is still wrong.